Title : Suite Sudarmoricaine
Text : '''''Suite Sud-Armoricaine''''' is a [[Ribaldry|bawdy]] [[Music of Brittany|Breton song]] in [[Breton language|Breton]], popularized by [[Alan Stivell]] in the 1970s. It is the only song in Breton ever to make the number one [[Record chart|chart]] spot on French radio [[Europe 1]].<ref>{{fr}} Yves Pouchard, [http://www.harpographie.fr/documentsimageshtml/articlespresse/leparisien2009.pdf "Les noces d'émeraude d'Alan Stivell"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502233638/http://www.harpographie.fr/documentsimageshtml/articlespresse/leparisien2009.pdf |date=2014-05-02 }}, ''[[Le Parisien]]'', October 22, 2009</ref> The lyrics are from the ''Pardon Speied'' (the [[Pardon (ceremony)|Pardon]] of the village of [[Spézet]]) date from 1950s and they are in the public domain because the author is unknown.<ref>"Kanomp Uhel", 1996, Coop Breizh</ref> The song is originally a traditional Breton musical air.

==Lyrics ==
{{col-begin}}
{{col-2}}
;Breton<ref>[http://www.parolesmania.com/paroles_alan_stivell_8486/paroles_suite_sudarmoricaine_308890.html Lyrics, Breton and French]</ref>
E pardon Speied e oan bet <br/>
Ur plac'h yaouank am eus kavet

'Barzh ar park vras hon eus kousket <br/>
Ur verol bras am eus paket

D'an ospital on bet kaset <br/>
War an daol vras on bet lakaet

Ha ma lost bras 'zo bet troc'het <br/>
Dre ar prenestr eo bet kaset

Ur meil ki-bleiz 'zo tremenet <br/>
Ha ma lost bras e-neus debret

Ha ma lost bras e-neus debret <br/>
Hag ar c'hi-bleiz a zo marvet

{{col-2}}
;English
At the pardon of Spezet, I went <br/>
A young girl, I found

In a large field, we slept <br/>
The [[Syphilis|great pox]], I caught

At the hospital, I was sent <br/>
On a large table, I was placed

And my big cock was cut <br/>
Through the window, it was thrown

A huge wolf-dog rose <br/>
And my big cock, he ate

And my big cock, he ate <br/>
And dog-wolf is dead 
{{col-end}}

== Recordings ==

* Alan Stivell: albums ''[[À l'Olympia (Alan Stivell)|À l'Olympia]]'' (1972), ''[[Again (Alan Stivell album)|Again]]'' (1993 with [[Shane MacGowan]]), ''Back to Breizh'' (2000 in French).
* An Triskell as ''Suite Pourlette'' (album ''Musiques Celtiques'', 1973).
* Polish band [[Shannon (band)|Shannon]] (2000).
* Franco-Slovak band [[Roc'hann]] (album ''Skladby z nášho'', 2008).
*[[Nolwenn Leroy]] (album ''[[Bretonne (album)|Bretonne]]'', 2010).<ref>{{fr}}, [http://www.voici.fr/news-people/actu-people/nolwenn-leroy-chante-une-chanson-grivoise-suite-sudarmoricaine-401434 Nolwenn Leroy chante une chanson grivoise : « Suite Sudarmoricaine »], ''Voici.fr'', April 3rd 2011</ref>
*[[Beltaine_(band)|Beltaine]] (album [[Tríú]], 2010).
*[[Les Stentors]] (album ''Voyage en France'', 2012).
*[[Julien Jaffrès]] (album ''Rock'n Celtic Guitar'', 2012).

